8.9.0 — Purpose and Legal Basis
GDPR Article 17 grants data subjects the right to request erasure of their personal data when: (a) the data is no longer necessary for the purpose it was collected, (b) the subject withdraws consent and no other legal basis exists, (c) the subject objects to processing and no overriding legitimate interests exist, or (d) the data was unlawfully processed. The UK GDPR contains equivalent provisions post-Brexit.

This section defines the platform's erasure protocol: how requests are received and verified, which data is erased, which data is lawfully retained, how the immutable event ledger is reconciled with erasure obligations, how erasure is logged without creating a paradox, and what the data subject receives as confirmation.

THE FUNDAMENTAL TENSION — RESOLVED
The platform uses an append-only immutable event ledger as a core architectural invariant. GDPR Article 17 requires erasure. These are not irreconcilable. The resolution: the ledger records that events happened, structured as typed events with actor IDs and scope IDs. The personal data associated with those events — names, documents, descriptions — lives in domain tables that are erasable. The ledger entries themselves can have their PII-containing fields redacted while preserving the chain integrity. The ledger proves the platform behaved. It does not need to contain the traveler's passport number to do so.

8.9.1 — Scope
This protocol applies to any natural person whose personal data is processed by the platform, including: travelers who created accounts, travelers who were added as group participants, emergency contacts added by account holders, and any person whose data appears in evidence or claim documentation uploaded by an account holder.

This protocol does not apply to: corporate entity data (legal names, registered addresses — these are not personal data under GDPR), anonymized or aggregated data, or data that has already been anonymized as part of routine retention expiry.

8.9.2 — Request Intake and Verification
How requests are received
•In-platform: Privacy & Data Controls surface (Section 7.3 System & Utility Domain) has an explicit 'Request data erasure' action
•Email: a designated privacy contact email address (privacy@wayfarer.com or equivalent) receives written requests
•Support: support staff receiving erasure requests must route them to the Founder within 24 hours — support staff do not action erasure requests directly

Identity verification
•For authenticated requests (in-platform): session authentication is sufficient. The request is tied to the authenticated account.
•For unauthenticated requests (email): the requestor must provide: (a) email address associated with the account, (b) one piece of verifiable account information (e.g., a trip name, a date of signup). Step-up OTP sent to the registered email to confirm identity before proceeding.
•For requests on behalf of a minor or incapacitated person: guardian or legal representative must provide documentation of authority. Founder reviews before proceeding.

Response timeline
•Acknowledgment: within 72 hours of request receipt
•Completion: within 30 days of verified request (GDPR Article 12 requirement)
•Extension: if complexity or volume requires extension, the data subject is notified within the initial 30-day window with an explanation. Maximum extension: 2 additional months (total 3 months from request).

