8.9.4 — Event Ledger Redaction Protocol
The event ledger is append-only. No rows are ever deleted. Erasure of PII within ledger rows is performed through a separate erasure_redaction_log table rather than in-place mutation. This preserves ledger chain integrity while satisfying Article 17 for the PII content.

Mechanism
•Step 1: Identify all event_ledger rows where previous_state or resulting_state JSONB contains PII fields for the erasure subject
•Step 2: For each identified row: write a row to erasure_redaction_log with: event_id, erasure_record_id, field_path, original_hash (SHA-256 of the original field value — proves the field existed without reproducing it), redacted_at, redacted_by
•Step 3: Update previous_state and resulting_state in the identified event_ledger rows — replace PII field values with the string '[ERASED — erasure_record_id: {id}]'
•Step 4: Recompute checksum for each updated row. The new checksum reflects the post-redaction state. The erasure_redaction_log records both the original checksum and the post-redaction checksum for audit purposes.
•Step 5: The event_id chain, event_type, timestamps, and scope_ids are never modified. The chain remains intact and replayable.

IMPORTANT — ACTOR_ID ANONYMIZATION
event_ledger.actor_id references auth.users. When an account is deleted, the actor_id in ledger rows is replaced with a stable anonymous identifier (a UUID derived from a one-way hash of the original account_id + a platform secret). This means 'this action was taken by someone' is preserved, but 'that someone was Christian Doe' is not. The anonymized ID is consistent across all ledger rows for the same original actor, so replay and causality analysis remain intact.

erasure_redaction_log table (required migration)
CREATE TABLE erasure_redaction_log with fields: redaction_id (uuid PK), erasure_record_id (uuid — groups all redactions from one erasure request), event_id (uuid FK → event_ledger), field_path (text — JSONPath to the redacted field), original_field_hash (text — SHA-256 of original value), pre_redaction_checksum (text), post_redaction_checksum (text), redacted_at (timestamptz), redacted_by (uuid — the system process that executed erasure, logged as system actor). RLS: SELECT for authenticated. No INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE policies — written only by erasure RPC.

8.9.5 — Lawful Retention Exceptions
GDPR Article 17(3) permits retention despite an erasure request where data is necessary for: (a) exercising freedom of expression, (b) compliance with a legal obligation, (c) public health purposes, (d) archiving, research, or statistical purposes in the public interest, or (e) establishment, exercise, or defence of legal claims.

The platform relies on the following Article 17(3) exceptions:

Exception	What Is Retained	Duration	How Subject Is Notified
Legal obligation (Article 17(3)(b)) — financial records	Claim financial outcomes (amounts, dates), payment records, credit ledger	7 years from transaction — standard financial record retention	Erasure confirmation states: 'Financial transaction records are retained for 7 years per legal requirement. These contain no personally identifying information beyond what is required for the financial record.'
Legal obligation — audit trail	Event ledger entries (redacted per 8.9.4), interpretive trace decision fingerprints	7 years from event	Erasure confirmation states: 'Audit trail records are retained to demonstrate platform behavior. Personal data within these records has been erased. The records prove we acted correctly — they do not reproduce your personal information.'
Defence of legal claims (Article 17(3)(e)) — active dispute hold	Any evidence file or document subject to an active dispute with an airline, insurer, or card issuer	Until dispute resolution + 90 days	'One or more documents are subject to an active dispute hold and cannot be erased until the dispute closes. You will be notified when these are erased. Estimated resolution: [date if known].'
Legal hold	Any data subject to a lawful legal hold order	Duration of hold	'Certain data is subject to a legal hold. We cannot provide details of the hold. Erasure of affected data is suspended for its duration.'

8.9.6 — Erasure Execution Sequence
The following steps execute atomically where possible, or in a logged sequence where atomicity across all systems is not achievable. Every step emits an event to the ledger.

Step	Action	Event Emitted	Rollback If Failed
1	Verify identity and validate request. Check for active dispute holds and legal holds.	pii_erasure_requested	N/A — validation only
2	Generate erasure_record_id. Create erasure request record with timestamp and verified identity method.	pii_erasure_initiated	Cancel erasure
3	Erase T1/T2 fields: passport images, policy document files, evidence files — delete from object storage. Log deletion confirmation.	pii_erasure_storage_purged	Re-attempt storage deletion. Alert Founder if storage deletion fails.
4	Null/erase PII fields in domain tables (Trip, Policy, Incident, Evidence, Claim, Contact) per Section 8.9.3 field register.	pii_erasure_domain_tables_processed	Re-attempt. Alert Founder if domain table erasure fails.
5	Execute event ledger redaction per Section 8.9.4. Recompute checksums. Write erasure_redaction_log.	pii_erasure_ledger_redacted	Re-attempt. Ledger redaction failure is a critical alert.
6	Anonymize actor_id in event ledger per 8.9.4 note.	pii_erasure_actor_anonymized	Re-attempt.
7	Mark all ITR records for this account with pii_redacted = true.	pii_erasure_itr_flagged	Re-attempt.
8	Apply dispute hold and legal hold exceptions — document what was NOT erased and why.	pii_erasure_exceptions_recorded	N/A — documentation step
9	Generate erasure confirmation document: what was erased, what was retained, legal basis for retention, date of completion, erasure_record_id for reference.	pii_erasure_completed	N/A — confirmation step
10	Deliver confirmation to data subject: in-platform notification if account still active; email if account being deleted; PDF available for download for 30 days.	pii_erasure_confirmation_delivered	Re-attempt delivery. Log failure.

8.9.7 — Behavioral Invariants
ID	Rule
E-I-01	Erasure requests are processed within 30 days of verified receipt. No exception without notification to the data subject and documented reason for extension.
E-I-02	The event ledger is never directly deleted. PII is redacted from ledger field values via the erasure_redaction_log mechanism. Chain integrity is preserved.
E-I-03	Every erasure request is assigned a unique erasure_record_id. This ID appears in the confirmation to the data subject and in every event emitted during erasure. It is the audit trail for the erasure itself.
E-I-04	Files deleted from object storage (passport images, policy documents, evidence files) have their deletion confirmed and logged. A deletion confirmation token is stored in the erasure record. If deletion cannot be confirmed, the Founder is alerted immediately.
E-I-05	Retained data is explicitly disclosed to the data subject in the erasure confirmation. The data subject is never left wondering what was kept.
E-I-06	Dispute holds and legal holds are documented at the time of erasure. When a hold lifts, the platform automatically proceeds with the deferred erasure and notifies the data subject.
E-I-07	The platform does not require the data subject to justify their erasure request. Verification of identity is required. Justification is not.
E-I-08	Erasure of one account does not erase data about the account holder that appears in another user's records (e.g., a person listed as an emergency contact in someone else's account). Each account's data is erased independently.
E-I-09	This protocol is reviewed annually and updated if the platform's data model changes materially. The per-object field register in Section 8.9.3 must be updated whenever new PII fields are added to any Section 3.2 object.

